    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i'm mostly worried about the corners and the areas where the joints meet the ceiling. sometimes it feels like something is catching or creating these weird little gaps or tiny holes right where the tape meets the mud. how do i make sure those spots stay tight and flush?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Those little gaps and holes at the corners and ceiling joints are usually caused by a few things, and you need to treat them like a small, tricky patch job. First, make sure your paper tape is pressed down *firmly* into the seam. If you're using fiberglass mesh tape, make sure it's fully embedded. When you're applying the mud, don't just slap it on; use a putty knife to firmly press the compound into those tight spots. You can use a small, sharp tool—like a thin putty knife or even a stiff piece of plastic—to gently scrape away any loose material or air pockets right at the seam line before you apply the next coat.",
      "source": "target",
